# ALM Mapping — {Agent Name}

## Work product → ALM hierarchy mapping

The project's hierarchy is declared in `projects/{p}/project.config.yaml alm.hierarchy`. For ADO this is typically `[Epic, Feature, "User Story", Task]`; for JIRA `[Initiative, Epic, Story, "Sub-task"]`.

How this agent's outputs map to the hierarchy:

| Local artefact | Maps to ALM level |
|---|---|
| Spec | L1 (Epic / Initiative) |
| Plan L2 sections | L2 (Feature / Epic) |
| Plan L3 sections | L3 (User Story / Story) |
| Task cards | L4 (Task / Sub-task) |
| Test cases | Test case under suite under plan |

## Section ID conventions

Every plan/TDD section carries a stable section ID (e.g., `FR-NN`, `TS-NN`). The ID is the durable link between markdown and ALM — `work-items.yaml` carries the markdown-section-ID ↔ ALM-ID mapping.

`doc_lint` rule: **no inline ALM IDs in markdown** — section IDs only. Mapping lives in `work-items.yaml`.

## Status mapping

| Local state | ADO state | JIRA state |
|---|---|---|
| draft | New | To Do |
| approved | Active | In Progress |
| implemented | Resolved | Done |
| documented | Closed | Closed |

(Exact mapping should be tuned per project; this is a starter.)

## Priority mapping

Local priority labels map to ALM priority integers per `project.config.yaml alm.priorityMap`. Don't invent custom priorities — stick to the configured set.

## /alm-extract output

When `/alm-extract` runs in this agent, it produces a `handoff` (schema: `handoff.v1`) targeted at the `alm` agent with:
- Source file references (spec, plan, TDD, task folder, test-plan folder)
- One `extractItem` per work-item-to-be-pushed, with `alm-action` ∈ {create, update, no-change}
- Section-ref backlinks for traceability

See [design/agents/alm.md](../../design/agents/alm.md) for the full ALM-side workflow.
